            <biogHist>
                <p>Roderick MacNeil was born c1790 to Donald and Ann MacNeil n√©e NacNeil. Roderick
                    followed his father in being a crofter. The earliest record of Roderick MacNeil,
                    aged 45, is from the 1841 Census where it indicates that he was living with his
                    wife Flora (aged 40) with his nine children: John (22), a fisherman, Anne (20),
                    a fisherwoman, Michael (20), Alexander (20), Mearon [Marion] (12), Anthony (10),
                    Donald (8), Eoin (6) and Rory (5) on Mingulary. The 1851 Census indicates that
                    Roderick was crofting three acres of land and is now only supporting his wife,
                    three sons Anthony, Donald and John (Eoin), and a grandson, Donald (4). In 1861
                    the family are still present on Mingulay with their children Donald and Rory,
                    and two grandchildren Donald and Rory. Carmichael acquired much information of
                    Mingulary from Roderick in 1868, and again in May 1871 when Roderick told him of
                    the song 'Taigh Mor Thunga'. Carmichael also notes that Roderick was also known
                    as 'Ruarai mac Dhonuil' or 'Ruarai an ruma' (on account of a hogshead of rum he
                    found on the shore 'from the contents of which he nearly died'). By 1871
                    Roderick was a widower and pauper and was living with one of his sons (not
                    identified in the Census) and his family. In March 1875 Roderick MacNeil died at
                    the age of 95 of natural causes, and his son-in-law James McNeil signed the
                    certificate.</p>
